		<li class="comment even depth-5 parent" id="comment-3649">
				<div id="div-comment-3649" class="comment-body">
				<div class="comment-author vcard">
				<cite class="fn"><a href='https://coinbr.com/about' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>jurov</a></cite> <span class="says">says:</span>		</div>

		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://www.loper-os.org/?p=988&amp;cpage=1#comment-3649">October 15, 2012 at 3:01 pm</a></div>

		<p>Still I see big practical problems. When the seller of the hardware (or the exchange, if the hardware is, say,  priced in USD) decides to accepts coins with unexpired bonds, they:<br />
1. must assess the risk (expensive)<br />
2. can&#8217;t just throw the coins on the market but must somehow accurately communicate the risk to potential buyers (expensive), or combine multiple kinds of bonded coins into some financial instrument and sell that (like those mortgage-backed securities, we all so fondly remember).</p>
<p>So IMHO it isn&#8217;t workable and it&#8217;s just simpler to raise unmarked coins for such a project.</p>

